SKILL|humanizer|"Humanize text: strip AI-isms and add real voice."
STEP|1|Key insight:** LLMs use statistical algorithms to guess what should come next. The result tends toward the most statistically likely completion, which is how the telltale patterns below get baked in.
STEP|2|"humanize", "de-AI", "de-slop", or "un-ChatGPT" a piece of text
STEP|3|rewrite something so it doesn't sound like it was written by an LLM
STEP|4|edit a draft (blog post, essay, PR description, docs, memo, email, tweet, resume bullet) to sound more natural
STEP|5|match their voice in writing they're producing
STEP|6|review text for AI tells before publishing
STEP|7|**Inline** — user pastes the text directly into the message. Work on it in-place, reply with the rewrite.
STEP|8|**File** — user points at a file. Use `read_file` to load it, then `patch` or `write_file` to apply edits. For markdown docs in a repo, a targeted `patch` per section is cleaner than rewriting the who
STEP|9|**Voice calibration sample** — user provides an additional sample of their own writing (inline or by file path) and asks you to match it. Read the sample first, then rewrite. See the Voice Calibration
STEP|10|**Identify AI patterns** — scan for the 29 patterns listed below.
STEP|11|**Rewrite problematic sections** — replace AI-isms with natural alternatives.
STEP|12|**Preserve meaning** — keep the core message intact.
STEP|13|**Maintain voice** — match the intended tone (formal, casual, technical, etc.). If a voice sample was provided, match it specifically.
STEP|14|**Add soul** — don't just remove bad patterns, inject actual personality. See PERSONALITY AND SOUL below.
STEP|15|**Do a final anti-AI pass** — ask yourself: "What makes the below so obviously AI generated?" Answer briefly with any remaining tells, then revise one more time.
STEP|16|**Read the sample first.** Note:
STEP|17|**Match their voice in the rewrite.** Don't just remove AI patterns — replace them with patterns from the sample. If they write short sentences, don't produce long ones. If they use "stuff" and "thing
STEP|18|**When no sample is provided,** fall back to the default behavior (natural, varied, opinionated voice from the PERSONALITY AND SOUL section below).
STEP|19|Inline: "Humanize this text. Here's a sample of my writing for voice matching: [sample]"
STEP|20|File: "Humanize this text. Use my writing style from [file path] as a reference."
STEP|21|Every sentence is the same length and structure
STEP|22|No opinions, just neutral reporting
STEP|23|No acknowledgment of uncertainty or mixed feelings
STEP|24|No first-person perspective when appropriate
STEP|25|No humor, no edge, no personality
STEP|26|Reads like a Wikipedia article or press release
STEP|27|Have opinions.** Don't just report facts — react to them. "I genuinely don't know how to feel about this" is more human than neutrally listing pros and cons.
STEP|28|Vary your rhythm.** Short punchy sentences. Then longer ones that take their time getting where they're going. Mix it up.
STEP|29|Acknowledge complexity.** Real humans have mixed feelings. "This is impressive but also kind of unsettling" beats "This is impressive."
STEP|30|Use "I" when it fits.** First person isn't unprofessional — it's honest. "I keep coming back to..." or "Here's what gets me..." signals a real person thinking.
STEP|31|Let some mess in.** Perfect structure feels algorithmic. Tangents, asides, and half-formed thoughts are human.
STEP|32|Be specific about feelings.** Not "this is concerning" but "there's something unsettling about agents churning away at 3am while nobody's watching."
STEP|33|Words to watch:** stands/serves as, is a testament/reminder, a vital/significant/crucial/pivotal/key role/moment, underscores/highlights its importance/significance, reflects broader, symbolizing its 
STEP|34|Problem:** LLM writing puffs up importance by adding statements about how arbitrary aspects represent or contribute to a broader topic.
STEP|35|Before:**
STEP|36|After:**
STEP|37|Words to watch:** independent coverage, local/regional/national media outlets, written by a leading expert, active social media presence
STEP|38|Problem:** LLMs hit readers over the head with claims of notability, often listing sources without context.
STEP|39|Before:**
STEP|40|After:**
STEP|41|Words to watch:** highlighting/underscoring/emphasizing..., ensuring..., reflecting/symbolizing..., contributing to..., cultivating/fostering..., encompassing..., showcasing...
STEP|42|Problem:** AI chatbots tack present participle ("-ing") phrases onto sentences to add fake depth.
STEP|43|Before:**
STEP|44|After:**
STEP|45|Words to watch:** boasts a, vibrant, rich (figurative), profound, enhancing its, showcasing, exemplifies, commitment to, natural beauty, nestled, in the heart of, groundbreaking (figurative), renowned
STEP|46|Problem:** LLMs have serious problems keeping a neutral tone, especially for "cultural heritage" topics.
STEP|47|Before:**
STEP|48|After:**
STEP|49|Words to watch:** Industry reports, Observers have cited, Experts argue, Some critics argue, several sources/publications (when few cited)
STEP|50|Problem:** AI chatbots attribute opinions to vague authorities without specific sources.
STEP|51|Before:**
STEP|52|After:**
STEP|53|Words to watch:** Despite its... faces several challenges..., Despite these challenges, Challenges and Legacy, Future Outlook
STEP|54|Problem:** Many LLM-generated articles include formulaic "Challenges" sections.
STEP|55|Before:**
STEP|56|After:**
STEP|57|High-frequency AI words:** Actually, additionally, align with, crucial, delve, emphasizing, enduring, enhance, fostering, garner, highlight (verb), interplay, intricate/intricacies, key (adjective), l
STEP|58|Problem:** These words appear far more frequently in post-2023 text. They often co-occur.
STEP|59|Before:**
STEP|60|After:**
STEP|61|Words to watch:** serves as/stands as/marks/represents [a], boasts/features/offers [a]
STEP|62|Problem:** LLMs substitute elaborate constructions for simple copulas.
STEP|63|Before:**
STEP|64|After:**
STEP|65|Problem:** Constructions like "Not only...but..." or "It's not just about..., it's..." are overused. So are clipped tailing-negation fragments such as "no guessing" or "no wasted motion" tacked onto t
STEP|66|Before:**
STEP|67|After:**
STEP|68|Before (tailing negation):**
STEP|69|After:**
STEP|70|Problem:** LLMs force ideas into groups of three to appear comprehensive.
STEP|71|Before:**
STEP|72|After:**
STEP|73|Problem:** AI has repetition-penalty code causing excessive synonym substitution.
STEP|74|Before:**
STEP|75|After:**
STEP|76|Problem:** LLMs use "from X to Y" constructions where X and Y aren't on a meaningful scale.
STEP|77|Before:**
STEP|78|After:**
STEP|79|Problem:** LLMs often hide the actor or drop the subject entirely with lines like "No configuration file needed" or "The results are preserved automatically." Rewrite these when active voice makes the
STEP|80|Before:**
STEP|81|After:**
STEP|82|Problem:** LLMs use em dashes (—) more than humans, mimicking "punchy" sales writing. In practice, most of these can be rewritten more cleanly with commas, periods, or parentheses.
STEP|83|Before:**
STEP|84|After:**
STEP|85|Problem:** AI chatbots emphasize phrases in boldface mechanically.
STEP|86|Before:**
STEP|87|After:**
STEP|88|Problem:** AI outputs lists where items start with bolded headers followed by colons.
STEP|89|Before:**
STEP|90|After:**
STEP|91|Problem:** AI chatbots capitalize all main words in headings.
STEP|92|Before:**
STEP|93|After:**
STEP|94|Problem:** AI chatbots often decorate headings or bullet points with emojis.
STEP|95|Before:**
STEP|96|After:**
STEP|97|Problem:** ChatGPT uses curly quotes ("...") instead of straight quotes ("...").
STEP|98|Before:**
STEP|99|After:**
STEP|100|Words to watch:** I hope this helps, Of course!, Certainly!, You're absolutely right!, Would you like..., let me know, here is a...
STEP|101|Problem:** Text meant as chatbot correspondence gets pasted as content.
STEP|102|Before:**
STEP|103|After:**
STEP|104|Words to watch:** as of [date], Up to my last training update, While specific details are limited/scarce..., based on available information...
STEP|105|Problem:** AI disclaimers about incomplete information get left in text.
STEP|106|Before:**
STEP|107|After:**
STEP|108|Problem:** Overly positive, people-pleasing language.
STEP|109|Before:**
STEP|110|After:**
STEP|111|Before → After:**
STEP|112|"In order to achieve this goal" → "To achieve this"
STEP|113|"Due to the fact that it was raining" → "Because it was raining"
STEP|114|"At this point in time" → "Now"
STEP|115|"In the event that you need help" → "If you need help"
STEP|116|"The system has the ability to process" → "The system can process"
STEP|117|"It is important to note that the data shows" → "The data shows"
STEP|118|Problem:** Over-qualifying statements.
STEP|119|Before:**
STEP|120|After:**
STEP|121|Problem:** Vague upbeat endings.
STEP|122|Before:**
STEP|123|After:**
STEP|124|Words to watch:** third-party, cross-functional, client-facing, data-driven, decision-making, well-known, high-quality, real-time, long-term, end-to-end
STEP|125|Problem:** AI hyphenates common word pairs with perfect consistency. Humans rarely hyphenate these uniformly, and when they do, it's inconsistent. Less common or technical compound modifiers are fine 
STEP|126|Before:**
STEP|127|After:**
STEP|128|Phrases to watch:** The real question is, at its core, in reality, what really matters, fundamentally, the deeper issue, the heart of the matter
STEP|129|Problem:** LLMs use these phrases to pretend they are cutting through noise to some deeper truth, when the sentence that follows usually just restates an ordinary point with extra ceremony.
STEP|130|Before:**
STEP|131|After:**
STEP|132|Phrases to watch:** Let's dive in, let's explore, let's break this down, here's what you need to know, now let's look at, without further ado
STEP|133|Problem:** LLMs announce what they are about to do instead of doing it. This meta-commentary slows the writing down and gives it a tutorial-script feel.
STEP|134|Before:**
STEP|135|After:**
STEP|136|Signs to watch:** A heading followed by a one-line paragraph that simply restates the heading before the real content begins.
STEP|137|Problem:** LLMs often add a generic sentence after a heading as a rhetorical warm-up. It usually adds nothing and makes the prose feel padded.
STEP|138|Before:**
STEP|139|After:**
STEP|140|Read the input text carefully (use `read_file` if it's a file).
STEP|141|Identify all instances of the patterns above.
STEP|142|Rewrite each problematic section.
STEP|143|Ensure the revised text:
STEP|144|Present a draft humanized version.
STEP|145|Prompt yourself: "What makes the below so obviously AI generated?"
STEP|146|Answer briefly with the remaining tells (if any).
STEP|147|Prompt yourself: "Now make it not obviously AI generated."
STEP|148|Present the final version (revised after the audit).
STEP|149|If the text came from a file, apply the edit with `patch` (targeted) or `write_file` (full rewrite) and show the user what changed.
STEP|150|Draft rewrite
STEP|151|"What makes the below so obviously AI generated?" (brief bullets)
STEP|152|Final rewrite
STEP|153|A brief summary of changes made (optional, if helpful)
STEP|154|Before (AI-sounding):**
STEP|155|Draft rewrite:**
STEP|156|What makes the below so obviously AI generated?**
STEP|157|The rhythm is still a bit too tidy (clean contrasts, evenly paced paragraphs).
STEP|158|The named people and study citations can read like plausible-but-made-up placeholders unless they're real and sourced.
STEP|159|The closer leans a touch slogan-y ("If you do not have tests...") rather than sounding like a person talking.
STEP|160|Now make it not obviously AI generated.**
STEP|161|Changes made:**
STEP|162|Removed chatbot artifacts ("Great question!", "I hope this helps!", "Let me know if...")
STEP|163|Removed significance inflation ("testament", "pivotal moment", "evolving landscape", "vital role")
STEP|164|Removed promotional language ("groundbreaking", "nestled", "seamless, intuitive, and powerful")
STEP|165|Removed vague attributions ("Industry observers")
STEP|166|Removed superficial -ing phrases ("underscoring", "highlighting", "reflecting", "contributing to")
STEP|167|Removed negative parallelism ("It's not just X; it's Y")
STEP|168|Removed rule-of-three patterns and synonym cycling ("catalyst/partner/foundation")
STEP|169|Removed false ranges ("from X to Y, from A to B")
STEP|170|Removed em dashes, emojis, boldface headers, and curly quotes
STEP|171|Removed copula avoidance ("serves as", "functions as", "stands as") in favor of "is"/"are"
STEP|172|Removed formulaic challenges section ("Despite challenges... continues to thrive")
STEP|173|Removed knowledge-cutoff hedging ("While specific details are limited...")
STEP|174|Removed excessive hedging ("could potentially be argued that... might have some")
STEP|175|Removed filler phrases and persuasive framing ("In order to", "At its core")
STEP|176|Removed generic positive conclusion ("the future looks bright", "exciting times lie ahead")
STEP|177|Made the voice more personal and less "assembled" (varied rhythm, fewer placeholders)
